[2] Bangladesh: vaccination postponed
Date: Tue 24 Mar 2020
Source: The Daily Star [abridged, edited]
https://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/news/another-child-dies-measles-rangamati-1884871


Another Tripura child died of measles in a remote area of Rangamati's Baghaichhari upazila.

PT, 9, passed away at her home in Lungthian Para early yesterday [23 Mar 2020], said Dr Istekhar Ahmed, upazila health and family planning officer.

Earlier, 5 indigenous children from remote Arun Tripura Para had died of measles since 26 Feb 2020. They all were from the Tripura community.

Local public representatives said children contracted measles in 5 paras of Sajek union early last month [February 2020].

Around 130 children, aged between 1 and 15 years, of Tripura and Chakma communities are infected with measles, said Harin Joy Tripura, a health assistant of Baghaichhari Upazila Health Complex.

The affected areas are Arun Tripura Para, Lungthian Tripua Para, Tarun Tripura Para, Kamalapur Chakma Para, and Kaikhya Tripura Para.

"A child died of measles in Arun Tripura Para on 26 Feb 2020. The 4 other children passed away on 27 Feb 2020, and 15, 16, 17 Mar 2020," said Harin Joy.

Community leaders alleged that neither doctors nor community health service providers visited their paras, as those were very remote areas. It takes around 10 hours to reach there from Rangamati town on foot. There is no other communication link between the town and the 5 paras.

Mithun Joy Tripura, karbari of Lungthian Para, said most of the children at their para were infected with measles. He said the villagers were panicked now.

Dr Istekhar said the sick children were still not out of danger as they were suffering from severe malnutrition.

Rangamati Civil Surgeon Bipash Khisa said they had a meeting with the programme manager of Expanded Program on Immunisation (EPI) in Baghaichhari yesterday [23 Mar 2020]. The meeting drew up a work plan to address the measles situation. He hoped the situation would improve soon.

Meanwhile, locals in Bandarban claimed that a child died of measles and that around 40 other people, including 33 children, were infected with the virus in a remote area of the hill district.

However, health officials claimed that the child died of an unknown disease.

In 2017, 9 children from the Tripura community died of measles in Chattogram's Sitakunda upazila.

[Byline: Sanjoy Kumar Barua]

