[5] Impact of unrelated outbreaks on measles and other diseases
Date: Wed 8 Jan 2020 [note date]
Source: BBC [abridged, edited]
https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51028791


The number of people killed by a measles epidemic in the Democratic Republic of Congo has passed 6000 [in 2019], the World Health Organization (WHO) has said.

The WHO says the epidemic is the world's largest and fastest moving.

Around 310 000 suspected measles cases have been reported since the start of 2019, the WHO says.

The Congolese government and the WHO launched an emergency vaccination programme last September [2019]. More than 18 million children under 5 were vaccinated across the country in 2019, the WHO says.

But poor infrastructure, attacks on health centres and a lack of access to routine healthcare have all hindered efforts to stop the spread of the disease.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[I am posting this report from January 2020 to highlight the effect of an outbreak of one disease on other diseases that are endemic but not in the limelight. The impact of diversion of funds and focus on Ebola to the neglect of other agents was also evident in the DRC in January 2019 by the incidence of cholera (15 331 cases, 287 deaths), measles (161 397 cases, 3117 deaths) and malaria, the leading cause of death in the DRC, which kills more than 48 000 people every year. (https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/29-08-2019-as-ebola-cases-reach-3000-in-drc-who-calls-on-partners-to-fulfill-promises-to-communities).

Because of limitation of funds and availability of health care workers, this is difficult, but public health practitioners and governments must try not to lose sight of endemic diseases afflicting the population. This can only be accomplished by maintaining a strong public health infrastructure with well-trained personnel. - Mod.LK]
